Lord Howe Island has a subtropical climate with warm summers (mean maximum temperature of approximately 25°C) and cool winters (mean maximum temperature of approximately 19°C). The island has reasonably high rainfall, with an annual average and median of about 1600 mm with rainfall erratic in summer and more or less uniform in winter. The driest months are November to February. There is a gradual transition from summer to winter conditions and vice versa (
Environment Australia 2002
). Winds are frequent and salt-laden, being moderate easterlies in summer and fresh to strong westerlies in winter. July is the windiest month and the winter months are subject to frequent gales and strong winds. Storm events and occasional cyclonic activity also affect the island ( Green 1994 ).

